# Cursor Fixer Rule - Read Test History

Read `AGENTS.md` (repo root) first — shared standards + process discipline. You are the **AUTHOR**:
you own ALL code fixes (including the fix-list Claude's review hands back). You do NOT write lessons
or memory — the REVIEWER (Claude) owns `_bug-catalog.md`, `bug-patterns.md`, and Serena/graph memory.

When asked to fix a bug or modify ANY file in `norviq/`, do this FIRST:

1. Identify the feature ID(s) that own the files being changed.
   Example: editing `norviq/engine/evaluator.py` -> F009 owns this.

2. Read `tests/.history/{FEAT}.md` for those features.
   Look for:
   - Bugs previously caught in this code (do not reintroduce)
   - Tests that must continue passing
   - Known limitations (document new ones, do not claim to fix what's deferred)

3. Read `tests/.history/_bug-catalog.md` + `docs/engineering/bug-patterns.md` for cross-cutting bug
   patterns (READ them — you do not write them; the reviewer curates both).
   Watch for:
   - Hardcoded fallbacks (OPA stub, default decision returns)
   - Regex shortcuts that skip real logic
   - Sub-second timeouts on subprocess calls
   - Memory state vs DB state mismatches
   - Cache TTLs masking real behavior

4. After making changes, run:
   - All tests listed in "What MUST Continue Passing" of relevant history files
   - All unit tests in the file you touched
   - Relevant integration tests

5. Update **your** history file `tests/.history/{FEAT}.md` with:
   - Tests you added
   - Bugs you caught
   - Files touched
   - New limitations (with `Phase 2:` prefix if deferred)
   Do NOT touch `_bug-catalog.md` / `bug-patterns.md` / Serena memory — those are reviewer-owned
   (Claude appends raw findings + promotes durable lessons on PASS; see `docs/WORKFLOW.md` Part F).

IMMUTABLE FILES - never edit:
- scripts/**
- prompts/**
- docs/norviq-ops-guide.md
- tests/.history/_bug-catalog.md (reviewer-owned — Claude appends findings; the author never writes it)
- docs/engineering/bug-patterns.md (reviewer-owned — curated lessons)

NEVER do:
- Add `@pytest.mark.xfail` without explaining the reason in a comment
- Remove existing tests without confirming with human
- Silently increase timeouts to hide subprocess issues
- Defer a doable in-scope fix to a backlog. Per AGENTS.md, APPLY doable fixes now; escalate only
  genuine spec/threat-model decisions to San. (No routing findings to `docs/backlog.md`.)
